## Introduction
This chapter introduces logical elements. *Doxee Template Designer *offers repeats and conditions (and condition branches as parts of conditions) as logical elements. When used in your template you can recognise logical elements by their orange colour.

## Step by Step
### Repeat
Data structures often contain multiple sets of data. In order to display these multiple sets, e.g. multiple customer entries, the *Repeat *element is used. In the previous chapter you created a template and added sample data. Those sample data contain repeated data too. In order to use them, insert a new *Block *[`7: Press ENTER while the cursor is behind the dynamic value element from the previous chapter or add a new Block from the Palette.`] and place a new *Table *inside it. Select *Add new &gt; Table Header *in the context menu of the table node. Insert three further columns as described in chapter [Tables](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-template-designer-user-guide-tables-1) and apply the following properties:

- 1st, 2nd, 5th and 6th column: 3 cm

- 3rd column: 1 cm

- 4th column: 2 cm

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 9. Add table header*

Delete the second row from the table header and enter the following labels to the cells in the remaining first line:

- Name

- Street

- ZIP

- City

- Phone

- Fax

Apply font size 8 pt, font style bold and some *background colour *to the block containing the table. Right click the node *example2/customer *in the Data Inputs View and choose *Copy *in

order to copy the XPath Expression for the selected node into the clipboard.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 10. Copying the XPath Expression of the selected node*

Right click the first row of the *Table Body *in the *Outline View *and choose *Wrap with &gt; Repeat*. Paste the copied expression into the upcoming dialog, e.g. via CTRL+V. Delete the second row in the table body.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 11. Wrap with Repeat*

You now see the row in the *Design Window *and in the *Outline View *wrapped within a *Repeat*. If you created a PDF preview you will not see anything but the table header. A *Repeat *itself is a loop that is repeated as many times, as the repeated node exists in the data structure. In order to see content in the output, values need to be specified to be displayed. Add *Dynamic Values *using the values of the repeated *customer *node to the rows cells.

> Important

If absolute paths are used and a PDF preview is created all cells contain the values of all instances of the repeated node. This is a very common error source. The repeat is meant to output the first customers data in the first row, the second customers in the second row, etc. To achieve this behaviour it is necessary to call nodes in the correct context. The *Repeat *has been set to a certain node and is meant to output *name*, *address*, etc. on every iteration. Drag the nodes from the *Data Inputs View *to the cells and delete the repeated part of the XPath expression or just enter the names of either node:

- name

- address

- zip

- city

- phone

- fax

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 12. Repeated Table Row*

Delete the second row of the table body and create a PDF Preview. In the preview all customer entries from the XML data source are shown.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

*Figure 13. Repeated data in the PDF preview*

### Conditions
Creating a condition is simple. You can either use the *Condition *element from the *Palette *and drag it to any place in the template or like the *Repeat *choose to wrap an element with a *Condition *using the context menu.

In order to demonstrate the use of a *Condition *right click the table row contained by the *Repeat *element in the *Outline View *and select *Wrap with &gt; Condition*. Enter name != 'John Doe' in the dialog that opens.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

*Figure 14. Add Condition*

Create a PDF preview. The line containing the data of *John Doe *is not displayed. Further *Condition Branches *can be added from the *Palette *or by right click on the condition. It is always possible to have one *Otherwise *branch. In this case leave the *XPath Expression *field empty. In order to switch between the displaying of *Condition Branches *use the context menu in the Outline View and select *Activate *in the context menu. To display a specific branch in the PDF preview, use the context menu &gt; *Fix for preview*. [`8: For information about fixing of condition branches see the user guide`]

Try this by creating a new condition branch and not entering an XPath expression. Copy the content of the first branch to the second one. Apply some random *background colour *to the copied *Table Row *through the properties. Create a PDF preview again and the line containing John Doe is highlighted using the background colour you chose.

## Things to Try
- Experiment with conditions with multiple condition branches

- Create conditions from the *Palette *and enter advanced XPath expressions. Also use the *Copy *function in the *Data Inputs View *and the *XPath Editor*, which can be opened via the menu *View &gt; XPath Editor*.

- Experiment with nested conditions
